          "title": "The cascade of violence — Gaal, the siege, the tower (9:25-49)",
          "body": "The dissolution of Abimelech's power follows the logic of the fable with grim literalness. The Shechemites who crowned him now rob his caravans (9:25), welcome his rival Gaal (9:26-27), and curse him at a pagan harvest festival (9:27). Gaal's rebellion is suppressed not by Abimelech directly but by Zebul, Abimelech's governor — the only loyal subordinate named in the chapter — who outmaneuvers Gaal with tactical deception (9:30-33) and then humiliates him when Abimelech's four-company ambush springs (9:34-41). But Abimelech's response to the restored control of Shechem is not clemency — it is annihilation. He returns the next day, slaughters the population in the fields, captures the city, razes it, and sows it with salt (9:42-45). The salt-sowing is a covenant-curse gesture of permanent desolation (Deuteronomy 29:23; Jeremiah 17:6). Then Abimelech burns the Tower of Shechem with approximately a thousand people inside, personally modeling the action he commands his troops to imitate (9:48-49). The detail that he carried the first branch on his own shoulder (9:48) is the narrator's portrait of a king who leads his army in atrocity. In this sequence, Jotham's fable-fire has become literal fire, and both parties of the original crime are consuming each other exactly as the curse predicted."
