          "title": "The millstone and the armor-bearer — the end of a tyrant (9:50-57)",
          "body": "Abimelech's death is staged with careful irony. He advances on the tower at Thebez with exactly the same tactic that succeeded at Shechem — approaching the entrance to burn it (9:52, cf. 9:49). The tactic that worked once becomes the occasion for his end. An unnamed woman (the narrator gives her no name, no tribe, no patronymic — she is simply 'a certain woman,' 9:53) drops an upper millstone from the roof. The millstone — a domestic object, the heaviest instrument in an ancient household's daily economy — crushes Abimelech's skull. His final act is to command his armor-bearer to finish him so that no one can say a woman killed him (9:54). The futility is profound: the narrator immediately attributes his death not to the woman, not to the armor-bearer, but to God (9:56). His last attempt at image-management is overruled by divine commentary. When Israel sees he is dead, they disperse — no mourning, no succession, no legacy. The chapter closes not on Abimelech's last moment but on the double divine verdict of 9:56-57: God repaid his wickedness; God returned the wickedness of Shechem. The curse of Jotham, spoken by a fugitive from a mountain no one was listening from, came upon them. The weakest word in the chapter — the one that fled to Beer — was the one that ruled history."
