        "excerpt": "Then God sent an evil spirit between Abimelech and the men of Shechem; and the men of Shechem dealt treacherously with Abimelech, so that the violence done to the seventy sons of Jerubbaal might come.",
        "body": "Verse 23 is one of the most theologically charged sentences in Judges. After three years of apparent divine absence from a chapter in which God has barely been mentioned, God acts — and He acts by sending ruach ra, an 'evil spirit' or 'spirit of animosity,' between Abimelech and the Shechemites. This raises an interpretive question that has exercised commentators from Calvin to the present: in what sense does God 'send evil'?\n\nThe text is not claiming God is the author of moral evil. The parallel is 1 Kings 22:19-23, where a lying spirit enters the mouth of Ahab's prophets — God's sovereign governance operates through the moral dispositions of wicked agents. God does not create the Shechemites' treachery ex nihilo; He removes the restraint that had held it in check and directs it toward His judicial purpose. Calvin's formulation remains accurate: God uses the devil and wicked persons as His instruments, yet in such a way that He acts justly while they act wickedly (Institutes II.4.2). The Shechemites were always treacherous; God now turned their treachery against the tyrant they had created.\n\nThe purpose clause of 9:24 is the narrator's theological key: 'so that the violence done to the seventy sons of Jerubbaal might come, and their blood might be laid on Abimelech their brother, who killed them, and on the men of Shechem, who strengthened his hands to kill his brothers.' Note the dual accountability. Abimelech killed. The Shechemites 'strengthened his hands' — the Hebrew chazaq yad (to strengthen the hand) is the language of material and political enablement. They funded, crowned, and politically legitimized the massacre. In God's court, the funder and the executioner share the same sentence. This principle has immediate application to any reader who has ever thought that providing resources for wickedness while not personally committing it constitutes innocence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ruach ra* (evil spirit, 9:23) — ra is the chapter's key word, appearing also in 9:56-57 as 'wickedness.' The same lemma that describes God's instrument of judgment (the evil spirit sent between them) also describes the wickedness God repays. The linguistic loop is the narrator's theological statement: God uses the evil itself as the means of evil's punishment."
